15
00:00:44,579 --> 00:00:46,960
gives you a sense
of perspective.

16
00:00:46,960 --> 00:00:50,740
One of the things that is
important to think about is

17
00:00:50,740 --> 00:00:54,329
that human beings like
to simplify things.

18
00:00:54,329 --> 00:01:01,429
We like to organize things
into clear groups--

19
00:01:01,429 --> 00:01:06,799
good/bad, friend/foe, us/them.

20
00:01:06,799 --> 00:01:12,979
And sometimes, this type of
binary thinking gets us into

21
00:01:12,980 --> 00:01:16,740
quite faulty conclusions about
ourselves and about our

22
00:01:16,739 --> 00:01:17,589
counterparts.

23
00:01:17,590 --> 00:01:21,170
And we tend to blow out of all
proportion their negative

24
00:01:21,170 --> 00:01:23,960
traits, and perhaps
overemphasize our

25
00:01:23,959 --> 00:01:26,119
own positive ones.

26
00:01:26,120 --> 00:01:29,880
This idea of complexity in
negotiation is worth pausing

27
00:01:29,879 --> 00:01:30,979
and thinking about.

28
00:01:30,980 --> 00:01:32,840
Negotiations are complex.

29
00:01:32,840 --> 00:01:34,170
They're rarely black
and white.

30
00:01:34,170 --> 00:01:37,239
And there's often this grey
territory, this ambiguous

31
00:01:37,239 --> 00:01:42,189
territory that we need to
somehow negotiate and manage

32
00:01:42,189 --> 00:01:45,230
carefully, without leaping
to conclusions.

33
00:01:45,230 --> 00:01:48,350
Be conscious of when you're
leaping to conclusions.

34
00:01:48,349 --> 00:01:51,819
Let me give you a couple of
examples of how we do this.

35
00:01:51,819 --> 00:01:55,379
One is what's called the
attribution error.

36
00:01:55,379 --> 00:01:58,359
And the attribution error
often occur is in

37
00:01:58,359 --> 00:02:01,719
cross-cultural negotiations,
which we'll come back to later

38
00:02:01,719 --> 00:02:02,920
in the course.

39
00:02:02,920 --> 00:02:06,480
But attribution error's
essentially this--

40
00:02:06,480 --> 00:02:11,490
I blame you for your negative
behavior on the sort of person

41
00:02:11,490 --> 00:02:15,080
you are, or the sort of group
you're a member of.

42
00:02:15,080 --> 00:02:19,110
So I might say, oh, that's a
typical bean counter view of

43
00:02:19,110 --> 00:02:20,990
the world if I'm referring
to an accountant

44
00:02:20,990 --> 00:02:22,670
or a financial manager.

45
00:02:22,669 --> 00:02:26,219
Or that's such an HR fluffy way
of looking at the world.

46
00:02:26,219 --> 00:02:30,830
Or you only think that way
because of whatever group

47
00:02:30,830 --> 00:02:32,469
you're a part of.

48
00:02:32,469 --> 00:02:36,770
And at the same time, my own
negative behavior, I

49
00:02:36,770 --> 00:02:40,096
rationalize as being caused
by the situation--

50
00:02:40,096 --> 00:02:42,219
oh, I was under a
lot of stress.

51
00:02:42,219 --> 00:02:44,240
Oh, I'm not normally
like that.

52
00:02:44,240 --> 00:02:47,150
So we tend to leap to
conclusions about the other

53
00:02:47,150 --> 00:02:49,260
side, and we draw stereotypes.

54
00:02:49,259 --> 00:02:52,409
And we blame their behavior
on the group membership.

55
00:02:52,409 --> 00:02:55,590
This is what's called the
ultimate attribution error.

56
00:02:55,590 --> 00:02:59,870
We need to think beyond just
black and white stereotypes

57
00:02:59,870 --> 00:03:02,349
about human behavior if we're
going to get our thinking

58
00:03:02,349 --> 00:03:05,030
right and become effective
negotiators.

59
00:03:05,030 --> 00:03:07,560
Let me give you another example
of where we can

60
00:03:07,560 --> 00:03:10,090
