65
00:03:25,610 --> 00:03:27,535
Let's take a typical example.

66
00:03:27,534 --> 00:03:32,129
If we've got the issue
in the center here--

67
00:03:32,129 --> 00:03:34,060
let's say it's a community
development.

68
00:03:34,060 --> 00:03:36,199
It might be a new bridge.

69
00:03:36,199 --> 00:03:39,030
It might be extending
the licensing laws

70
00:03:39,030 --> 00:03:40,300
on the local pub.

71
00:03:40,300 --> 00:03:43,060
It could be a bike
track through the

72
00:03:43,060 --> 00:03:44,439
center of the city--

73
00:03:44,439 --> 00:03:45,460
some sort of issue.

74
00:03:45,460 --> 00:03:47,800
Often, development projects
are like this.

75
00:03:47,800 --> 00:03:55,660
And then you have a range of
different people who all have

76
00:03:55,659 --> 00:03:59,210
a stake, or an interest,
in the outcome.

77
00:03:59,210 --> 00:04:03,120
And these are community groups
who have some input to the

78
00:04:03,120 --> 00:04:06,409
issue, either blocking the
issue, or having some input,

79
00:04:06,409 --> 00:04:08,479
or advocating for it, trying
to support it.

80
00:04:08,479 --> 00:04:12,579


81
00:04:12,580 --> 00:04:16,350
This is what's called a
multiparty negotiation.

82
00:04:16,350 --> 00:04:20,390
What we often see happen in
these types of situations is

83
00:04:20,389 --> 00:04:23,219
the formulation of
coalitions--

84
00:04:23,220 --> 00:04:27,100
that is, groups join
together to add

85
00:04:27,100 --> 00:04:28,800
weight to their argument.

86
00:04:28,800 --> 00:04:33,520
And in doing so, what we often
find is that they need to make

87
00:04:33,519 --> 00:04:36,979
compromises so that they can
find that common ground.

88
00:04:36,980 --> 00:04:41,560
And we often have a tendency to
want to simplify a complex

89
00:04:41,560 --> 00:04:45,730
issue into a us/them,
yes/no proposition.

90
00:04:45,730 --> 00:04:48,480
So rather than this negotiation
being a multiparty

91
00:04:48,480 --> 00:04:55,590
issue, people want to make it
a two-party negotiation, us

92
00:04:55,589 --> 00:05:04,679
and them, for or against.

93
00:05:04,680 --> 00:05:07,139
And it's rarely as
simple as that.

94
00:05:07,139 --> 00:05:11,099
So we really need to watch out
for this simplification,

95
00:05:11,100 --> 00:05:14,620
because we will obscure the
key issues for individual

96
00:05:14,620 --> 00:05:18,350
parties, and we'll often create
overly simplistic

97
00:05:18,350 --> 00:05:21,600
solutions that may not be
effective and lasting.

